TY  - JOUR
T1  - Some Problems in using Diffusion Models for New Products
AU  - Bernhardt, Irwin
AU  - Mackenzie, Kenneth D.
Y1  - 1972/10/01
PY  - 1972
DA  - 1972/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.19.2.187
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.19.2.187
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 187
EP  - 200
VL  - 19
IS  - 2
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper analyzes some of the problems involved in using diffusion models to formulate marketing strategies for introducing new products. Though future work in this area appears justified, there are many unresolved problems which limit application. First, there is no theory for adoption and diffusion processes. Such a theory is outlined in this paper. Secondly, the present models are too restrictive and do not include the variables that a marketing manager has at his disposal. Six models which remove some of the theoretical and methodological restrictions are therefore presented. The marketing implications of the assumptions in the models are discussed.
AB  - This paper analyzes some of the problems involved in using diffusion models to formulate marketing strategies for introducing new products. Though future work in this area appears justified, there are many unresolved problems which limit application. First, there is no theory for adoption and diffusion processes. Such a theory is outlined in this paper. Secondly, the present models are too restrictive and do not include the variables that a marketing manager has at his disposal. Six models which remove some of the theoretical and methodological restrictions are therefore presented. The marketing implications of the assumptions in the models are discussed.
